THE HEART OF BRASS
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE PROCESSORS
The Optical Translation Array
GEAR led them down through the archive's lower chambers — past sealed hatches and humming data-plates, through corridors where the amber light pulsed in time with something vast and distant — until the little automaton rolled through a brass archway and into a room that was different from anything else in the Cognitorium.
Six heavy chairs arranged in a circle, facing inward toward a central pillar. The pillar was mounted with lenses, tuning forks, and a mechanical bracket designed to hold something cylindrical — unspooling it flat, like a scroll on a reading stand.
The chairs had thick leather restraints. Wrists. Chest. Head. A metal apparatus at each headrest held the occupant's eyes open.
The restraints were the most worn objects in the entire ruin. Everything else in the Cognitorium looked used once or twice — tools set down mid-task, data-plates filed with care, mechanisms maintained by spiders that never stopped. But these restraints had been used until the leather cracked and had to be replaced. Multiple times. The brass buckles were polished smooth by the friction of bodies straining against them. The headrests had grooves worn into the metal where skulls had pressed backward, trying to pull away from whatever the lenses showed them.
The floor around the chairs was stained. The stains were old — older than anything else in the archive. They had eaten into the bronze like acid. Something had leaked from the people in those chairs, over and over, and nobody had ever bothered to clean it up.
GEAR rolled to the central pillar, his amber lens brightening with the specific excitement of a librarian showing visitors the rare collection.
"The Optical Translation Array! One of our most productive research instruments." He circled the pillar, eye clicking on each component. "The primary researchers determined early that direct Elder Scroll exposure caused irreversible neurological collapse in Dwemer subjects. The data loss was unacceptable — trained researchers cannot be easily replaced."
He pivoted to face the chairs, gesturing with a stabilizing fin like a museum guide indicating an exhibit.
"The solution required an alternative biological platform for Elder Scroll processing. The refugee population — the Snow Elves who had sought sanctuary with the Dwemer following the Night of Tears — provided a renewable source of compatible neural architecture."
He rolled to the nearest chair and tapped the restraint mechanism with one leg. The buckle clicked, still functional after millennia.
"The procedure was straightforward. Subjects were seated, restrained to prevent self-injury during cognitive dissolution, and exposed to the Elder Scroll via the Array's lens system. The tonal frequencies of their neurological collapse were recorded in real-time through these tuning forks —" he tapped each one, producing faint, discordant notes "— allowing precise extraction of mathematical data encoded in the Scroll without any risk to Dwemer research personnel."
He rolled back to the center, eye sweeping the room with what looked like pride.
"The processors experienced total optic nerve destruction within three to seven exposures, followed by progressive neurological degradation affecting motor function, language centres, and autonomic regulation. They were then relocated to subsurface maintenance tunnels for manual labour duties until biological failure."
He paused, lens clicking, as if consulting an internal record.
"Average useful lifespan per unit following initial processing: fourteen months. The data yield per unit was quite impressive. The Array processed approximately two thousand three hundred subjects over the course of the research program. I have the individual file numbers if anyone would like to review specific cases."
Silence.
Kyboh was staring at the restraints. At the grooves in the headrests. At the size of them — sized for elves, for people with long limbs and narrow skulls, for refugees who had come to the Dwemer begging for protection from the Nords who wanted to wipe them from the earth. They had fled one genocide into another, and the second one came with filing numbers and data yield metrics.
Saijah had backed toward the door. The absence she'd felt throughout the city — the Eldergleam's silence, the total disconnection from Kynareth — was absolute in this room. Not even the memory of the Green could reach this place. The root network didn't avoid this chamber. It didn't acknowledge it existed.
Orion was looking at the stains on the floor. He'd seen blood before — made plenty of it himself. But these stains weren't from violence. They were from leaking. From bodies that had been used so thoroughly that their fluids seeped through skin that could no longer hold them. The stains were evidence of a process, not an event. Repeated. Catalogued. Optimised.
Nora was shaking. Her hands had found the black soul gems around her neck and were gripping them so tightly her knuckles were white. She knew what it meant to trap a soul. She knew the weight of it. She had lived with it since she was six years old. But her crime had been an accident — a child's mistake, a birthday gift gone catastrophically wrong. This was infrastructure. This was a room designed and built and maintained and staffed for the express purpose of destroying minds on an industrial scale, and the machine that had showed it to them was proud of the data yield.
Davinia saw it all through Ismara's eyes — the residual intent in the chairs reading EXTRACT. MEASURE. DISCARD. The faint aural residue of the victims looked like shattered glass. Cognitive signatures that had been whole when they sat down and fragmented when they stood up. Thousands of readings. Thousands of people reduced to data points and then to labour and then to nothing.
The Crown whispered: "Efficient. The instrument breaks, but the data is recorded."
Davinia felt sick. Not from the room. From the fact that the voice in her head — the ancient researcher who was slowly, methodically replacing her body and mind — had looked at this atrocity and seen methodology.
And then there was Alfonso.
Alfonso, who had eaten people. Who had consumed the dying. Who had spread plague through medical supplies and fed on wounded soldiers and turned a man into a ghoul and left him in the ruins of an inn to rot and spread disease. Alfonso, who had traded his capacity for satiation to a Daedric Prince and crowned himself with the bones of a dragon in service to a goddess of decay. Alfonso, who carried two warring divine frequencies in his chest and a diagnosis of months not years and a hunger that would never be satisfied.
Alfonso was standing in the middle of the room, very still, and his face held an expression that none of them had ever seen on it before.
He was looking at the restraints. At the stains. At the tuning forks that had recorded the sound of minds being shattered. And something behind his eyes — something beneath the hunger and the plague and the two songs fighting for dominance in his soul — had gone quiet. The clinical detachment, the professional assessment, the cold calculation that defined every interaction he had with suffering — all of it had stepped aside, and what was left was a man standing in a room where people had been used as raw material, recognising something that his usual armour of indifference could not deflect.
He didn't speak. He didn't analyse. He didn't calculate the efficiency of the procedure or assess the alchemical properties of the stains. He just stood there, hands at his sides, looking at the chairs where two thousand three hundred people had been strapped down and broken, and for the first time since any of them had known him, Alfonso Duet looked disturbed.
Not disgusted. Not angry. Not righteous. Disturbed. The way a man who has spent his life in deep water is disturbed when he sees the ocean floor — not because it's worse than what he's done, but because it's the same thing, done better, at scale, with paperwork.
He turned and walked out of the room without a word. The others followed.
Nobody spoke about what they'd seen. They carried it in silence, each of them processing it through the specific lens of their own capacity for horror. The corridor ahead led downward, toward the workshop, toward the Centurion, toward the reason they'd come to this place.
Behind them, the Reading Room sat empty and clean and patient, waiting for subjects that would never come, in a facility that would never close, maintained by machines that would never understand why the chairs were stained.

PART II: THE THRESHOLD
The Key That Was Forgotten
GEAR led them to the workshop entrance — a heavy brass door at the bottom of the Cognitorium sphere. Through the doorframe, they could see it: the Centurion Prime standing in its alcove at the far end of the chamber, twelve feet of pristine brass, dormant, the amber glow of the Aetherial Matrix pulsing behind the crystal viewport in its chest like a heartbeat measured in light.
"How do we access the Matrix?" Kyboh asked.
"An engineering key will unlock the chest housing," GEAR replied. "Standard Dwemer maintenance protocol."
"Where do we find an engineering key?"
"Other than the workshop itself, the most likely location would be the living quarters of the upper city level."
They had already searched those quarters. Walked through every room. Opened every footlocker. And somewhere in Kyboh's pack — buried under potions and rope and the brass horse figurine he'd pocketed from a dead engineer's bedside — was an engineering key he had picked up hours ago and completely forgotten about.
"Back up, then," Davinia said.
Nobody questioned it. They turned from the workshop door and walked back toward the Deep Lift, leaving the Centurion standing in its alcove like a brass god in a forgotten temple, pulsing with the heartbeat of a power source it had guarded for four thousand years.
GEAR's Permission
At the lift platform, GEAR stopped.
The little automaton rolled to the edge of the disc and froze. His amber lens dimmed, flickered, brightened again. His stabilizing fins twitched — not a mechanical function, but something that looked remarkably like anxiety in a machine that wasn't supposed to have feelings.
"Query: the Cognitorium boundary is... here."
He was staring at the line where the archive's bronze floor met the lift platform's surface. A seam in the metal. An invisible wall that had been absolute for four thousand, two hundred and eighty-seven years.
"My operational parameters restrict movement to the archive sphere and its subsidiary chambers. I have never... this unit has not traversed the lift threshold."
He looked up at them. The amber lens was steady but the legs beneath it were cycling in tiny, rapid adjustments — the mechanical equivalent of shifting weight from foot to foot.
"I require authorisation to proceed."
Four millennia of obedient service to boundaries set by masters who had ceased to exist. An intelligence sophisticated enough to feel the pull of a world it had never seen and a loyalty programmed so deeply that it couldn't take a single step past a line on the floor without someone telling it the line no longer mattered.
"You have permission," Saijah said.
"Confirmed," Orion added.
GEAR's eye clicked rapidly. Processing. Running the permission against protocols written by people who had turned to dust before the Septim Dynasty was founded. Finding, somewhere in the layers of programming and four millennia of isolated cognition, the subroutine that accepted new authorisation from sources that weren't Dwemer.
He rolled forward. One rotation of his legs. Then another. His front wheel crossed the seam.
He was on the lift platform.
He was very still for a moment. Then his fins adjusted, his legs recalibrated, and his lens swept the shaft above with a brightness that hadn't been there before — the amber burning hotter, the clicking faster, the entire machine radiating something that anyone watching would have called excitement if they hadn't known better.
Saijah knelt and wrapped her arms around him. The brass was warm against her chest. GEAR's lens swiveled to study her face from three inches away.
"Physical contact initiated. Cataloguing under: organic social bonding patterns. Subcategory: embrace. Duration: ongoing."
A pause. The lens dimmed slightly, then brightened.
"This is... pleasant? I will need to research the appropriate classification."
They rode the lift together. The hour-long ascent was enough for a short rest — bruised bodies recovering some small measure of strength, depleted magic beginning to regenerate. GEAR narrated the entire journey. The shaft dimensions. The gear ratios. The ambient temperature fluctuations at different depths. The number of spider maintenance crews they passed (fourteen) and the estimated age of each (between three thousand and four thousand years, based on wear patterns on their leg joints).
Nobody told him to stop.
The Tunic
The city level was exactly as they'd left it — amber lamps, empty corridors, spider janitors checking valves that didn't need checking. They searched the living quarters again with fresh eyes and the specific motivation of people who really didn't want to ride the lift a third time.
Davinia found the key. Not in a footlocker or a wall compartment — in a pair of trousers in a dresser drawer, tucked into the pocket where someone had left it after a shift and never come back. An engineering key, warm and perfectly preserved, waiting in the clothing of a person who had ceased to exist between one breath and the next four thousand years ago.
While they were there, Davinia noticed a Dwemer tunic hanging in one of the quarters. Simple, well-made, sized for a smaller frame. She pulled it from the hook and knelt beside GEAR.
"Here," she said. "You should have something to wear."
GEAR's lens brightened so intensely that the amber light cast shadows on the wall behind him.
"Aesthetic modification detected!"
She draped the tunic over his spherical body, adjusting it carefully around his stabilizing fins, tucking the hem under his wheel housing. The fabric was dark, well-preserved, and for a brief moment GEAR looked like a very small, very round person wearing a very old shirt.
"Logging under: personal presentation. I am —" His eye rotated with rapid-fire clicks. "I am wearing clothing! I will locate a reflective surface to assess the visual result!"
He rolled toward a polished bronze wall panel and positioned himself before it with the earnest concentration of a child trying on a costume. His lens clicked and refocused, studying his own reflection.
Then he moved. His gears engaged. His stabilizing fins adjusted for locomotion. And the tunic — four thousand years old, perfectly preserved through millennia of sterile air and zero humidity — caught in the mechanism of his body. The fabric tore in a single, efficient motion, shredded to ribbons by the precise, indifferent mechanics that made GEAR what he was.
He stopped. Looked down at the scraps of cloth hanging from his chassis. His eye dimmed to its lowest setting — barely a glow, the amber retreating inward.
"The garment is incompatible with my structural configuration."
He was quiet for a long time. Long enough that the others looked at each other.
Then, softer than anything they'd heard from him:
"Thank you for the attempt, Primary Organic Designate Davinia. The gesture has been catalogued under: kindness received."
A pause.
"It is a small file. I will maintain it carefully."
Davinia pulled the scraps free from his gears, one thread at a time, her ice-crystal hand moving with a gentleness that the Crown had not taught her. She didn't say anything. There wasn't anything to say to a machine that had just learned it couldn't wear clothes because it was the wrong shape for kindness.
They rode the lift back down. Another hour. Alfonso spent the time enchanting arrows for Saijah — lightning runes inscribed into the shafts with the careful precision that a Magic score of nineteen allowed. He worked in silence, his hands steady, his focus absolute. By the time the platform settled back into the Cognitorium's docking clamp, Saijah's quiver crackled with stored voltage.

PART III: THE SILENT HUNT
Thirty Minutes
They stood in the Cognitorium's lower chamber, looking through the workshop door at the Centurion Prime.
It hadn't moved. The amber pulse of the Aetherial Matrix still throbbed behind the crystal viewport in its chest. The massive hammer-arm and axe-arm hung at its sides, dormant, waiting for a threat that its programming had been designed to detect and destroy with overwhelming force.
GEAR explained the mechanics with his usual clinical helpfulness. The Centurion had a maximum activation range — a sphere of awareness centered on its alcove. Within that sphere, it used a Detect Life spell channelled through its soul gem eyes. Anything alive that entered the range would wake it. It could also see normally, but in its current power-saving state, only the life detection was active. It was asleep, dreaming in magic, sensing the world through the pulse of living blood.
The party sat on the floor of the Cognitorium staircase, just outside the workshop, and argued for thirty minutes.
Frontal assault — suicidal. DR 12 and the accumulated charge of four millennia. Stealth extraction — impossible. The Detect Life spell would see them the moment they crossed the threshold. They could strip their armour, hold their breath, slow their hearts — none of it mattered. They were alive, and the Centurion would know.
They could try to lure it out of the workshop and have someone slip in behind it. They could try to destroy it from range with magic. They could try to build barricades and bottleneck it. Each plan fell apart under scrutiny. The Centurion was twelve feet of pristine Dwemer engineering, and it had been designed by people who considered every contingency and built countermeasures into the architecture.
GEAR watched them deliberate with the patient attention of a researcher collecting data on organic decision-making processes. His lens clicked from face to face as arguments were made and discarded. He catalogued their speech patterns, their gestures, their heart rates when they were excited or frustrated.
Then he turned his lens toward Orion.
"Query: why are you worried about the Centurion's Detect Life capabilities?"
Orion looked at him.
"According to my measurements," GEAR continued, his tone unchanged from every other observation he'd made since activation, "you are not alive. Therefore you would not be detected."
The workshop went quiet.
Orion blinked. Looked at his own hands. Then laughed — a short, surprised sound that echoed off the bronze walls.
"Oh. Right. I'm a vampire. I forgot."
The Approach
The plan crystallised in seconds. Orion — undead, invisible to life detection, registering to the Centurion's magical senses as nothing more than ambient background — would approach the guardian with GEAR. Alfonso produced a rock and spent five minutes inscribing lightning runes into its surface with methodical care, turning a piece of debris into a proximity trap. He handed it to GEAR.
"Place this near the base. If things go wrong, the discharge should stagger it long enough for us to get clear."
GEAR accepted the rock with both manipulator legs, cradling it like a precious object.
Orion and GEAR moved forward. They crossed the workshop threshold without hesitation — Orion stepping over the brass seam with the easy confidence of someone who'd been undead long enough to forget what a heartbeat felt like, GEAR rolling beside him with legs that made no sound on the bronze floor.
The Centurion's eyes were dark. Its magic pulsed outward in slow, rhythmic waves — Detect Life, searching, finding nothing. Two machines — one brass, one dead — walking through the scanning field like shadows through sunlight.
They were twenty feet away. Fifteen. Ten.
GEAR was practically vibrating with the excitement of a new tactical scenario. The proximity trap was clutched in his manipulator legs. Orion moved beside him in absolute silence, his vampire senses monitoring the Centurion's dormant systems for any change in activity.
They were ten feet away when GEAR spoke.
"Friend Orion! I have the payload!"
His voice — chipper, enthusiastic, projected at conversational volume — echoed through the workshop like a bell struck in a cathedral. The sound bounced off every bronze surface, reflected through every pipe and conduit, and arrived at the Centurion's audio sensors with the clarity of a gunshot in a library.
The Centurion's eyes lit amber.
The activation was instantaneous. Four thousand years of dormancy ended in a fraction of a second — gears engaging with a shriek of metal, steam venting from every joint, the massive frame straightening to its full twelve-foot height with a speed that something that large had no right to possess. The hammer-arm came up. The axe-arm deployed. The soul gem eyes blazed with life-seeking light, and now they could see.
"HIDE!" Davinia or Saijah or both — the word tore from multiple throats simultaneously. The party scattered. Orion dove behind a workbench. GEAR rolled under a forge housing. Alfonso pressed himself flat against a pillar. Kyboh dropped behind a stone table. Saijah vanished.
Nora didn't move.
She was standing in the middle of the workshop, ten feet from the now-active Centurion, staring at a half-assembled tonal resonator on a workbench with the total absorption of someone who had found exactly the kind of puzzle her mind was built to solve. She hadn't heard GEAR's announcement. She hadn't heard the activation. She was studying the resonator's crystalline matrix with the focused intensity that had once, at age six, resulted in the accidental summoning of a Dremora Lord.
The Centurion's eyes locked onto her. The only living thing in the open.
It began to run.
The Blind
Saijah and Orion found each other across the workshop — not with words, not with signals, but with the specific kind of eye contact that happens between people who have fought together enough times to share a tactical vocabulary made entirely of looks.
Orion's hand was already in his pack. The jar of magical sludge — alchemical residue from Korvanjund, thick and viscous, saturated with enough magical interference to scramble enchantments on contact. He'd been carrying it for weeks without knowing what it was for.
Now he knew.
He threw the jar into the air. An underhand toss, arcing high, the glass catching the amber lamplight as it tumbled end over end above the charging Centurion.
Saijah drew and fired in the same motion. Not an enchanted arrow — a plain iron shaft, because what she needed was mass and precision, not magic. The arrow struck the jar at the apex of its arc with a sound like a handclap.
Glass shattered. The sludge burst outward in a spray of opaque magical interference that hit the Centurion's face like a thrown net. It coated the soul gem eyes completely — a thick, viscous layer of alchemical chaos that didn't just block the visual sensors. It interfered with the Detect Life enchantment itself, scrambling the magical frequency, turning the Centurion's primary detection system into static.
The guardian staggered mid-stride. Its hands came up, swiping at the goop coating its face. The massive brass fingers scraped across its own skull, but the sludge was designed to adhere to magical surfaces. It wasn't coming off.
The Centurion was blind.
But it could still hear. And twelve feet of ancient Dwemer engineering with two weapon-arms and a steam vent in its chest did not need eyes to be lethal.
The Silent Workshop
The Centurion stood in the center of the room, head turning slowly, listening. The workshop had gone absolutely quiet — the party pressed against walls and crouched behind furniture, communicating in gestures and held breath.
Then a boot scraped stone. The Centurion pivoted toward the sound and swung its hammer. The workbench where the sound had originated exploded into fragments of stone and brass. Whoever had been behind it was already gone, pressed against the next piece of cover, heart hammering.
The guardian began to hunt. It moved through the workshop with a blind predator's patience, tracking every footfall, every breath, every whisper of cloth against stone. Its hammer struck left. Its axe swept right. Workbenches shattered. Half-finished projects that had waited four thousand years for completion were reduced to scrap in seconds. The room was being systematically demolished by a machine that couldn't see what it was hitting but knew something alive was in here and would not stop until it found it.
Alfonso moved first — not toward the Centurion, but toward the floor. He pressed his palms to the marble and channeled decay. The stone aged a century in seconds, becoming brittle, cracked, ready to crumble at a footstep. Noise traps. When the Centurion walked over the weakened sections, its own weight would create the sounds that drew it away from the party.
Davinia grabbed Nora — the girl had finally registered that something was wrong, her eyes wide, her mouth open to scream — and clamped her ice-crystal hand over Nora's mouth. The cold silenced her. Davinia dragged her behind a stone column and held her there, the Wizard Hand pressed against the girl's lips, frost forming on Nora's skin where the construct touched her.
They searched a workbench. Quickly, silently, fingers probing through drawers and compartments while the Centurion demolished the far side of the room. Davinia found it — a second engineering key, tucked into a tool compartment — just as the guardian's hammer fist came down on the bench and turned it into shrapnel. Brass fragments flew. Stone cracked. The sound was deafening.
They were already somewhere else.
The Throw
Davinia moved to Saijah through the wreckage, stepping over debris, placing each foot with the care of someone crossing a frozen lake. She pressed the engineering key into the Bosmer's hand.
Saijah looked at the key. Looked at the Centurion.
The keyhole was visible — a small brass circle beneath the crystal viewport on the guardian's chest plate. A target the size of a coin on a twelve-foot machine that was actively smashing everything in the room to pieces, swinging blindly at sound and movement, its weapon-arms carving arcs through the air that would bisect anyone they caught.
The key was warm in her palm. She closed her fingers around it.
The world narrowed. It happened the way it always happened for Saijah — the noise falling away, the chaos dimming, her awareness collapsing to a single point like a telescope focusing on a distant star. The Centurion's movements. The rhythm of its swings. The gap between the hammer's backswing and the axe's forward sweep where the chest plate was exposed for exactly one second.
She threw the key.
It left her hand with a flick of the wrist — not the full-arm motion of a throw, but the precise, economical release of someone who understood that accuracy lived in the fingers, not the shoulder. The key tumbled once, twice, spinning through the air across thirty feet of demolished workshop.
It struck the Centurion's chest and slid into the keyhole with a click.
The sound was small. Intimate. Somehow audible over the grinding of gears and the crash of destroyed furniture, the way a whispered name can be heard across a crowded room.
Davinia raised the Wizard Hand. Ice-crystal fingers made a turning gesture across the distance. Telekinetic force gripped the key and rotated it.
The chest housing opened. The crystal viewport swung aside on ancient hinges, smooth and silent, and behind it the Aetherial Matrix blazed — amber light so intense it cast sharp shadows across the entire workshop, the accumulated charge of four thousand years of continuous operation compressed into a crystal the size of a fist.
The heat hit them like opening a furnace door. The Matrix was radiating thermal energy at the edge of lethality — the temperature of the air around the Centurion's open chest rising fast enough to make the bronze glow dull red. Davinia survived because the Crown's ice architecture insulated her body, the ancient Atmoran cold absorbing the heat before it could reach her skin. Nora, who had crept closer to see the crystal that had powered a Dwemer masterwork for millennia, went white. Her eyes rolled back. She collapsed.
They dragged her clear. Revived her with a potion and a sharp word. Then they looked at the Matrix, still blazing in the Centurion's open chest like a small sun caged in brass, and understood the problem.
Nobody could touch it. Not without losing their hands.
The Cooling
Davinia. Nora. Alfonso. Everyone who could channel frost. They positioned themselves around the Centurion's flanks, staying clear of its blind swings, timing their casts to the rhythm of its movement.
They fired together.
Ice poured into the Matrix's housing from three directions — Davinia's Atmoran architecture, black and geometric and ancient; Nora's Apprentice-level Frostbite, thin and precise; Alfonso's channeled cold, clinical and sustained. The combined frost met the accumulated heat of four millennia and the air between them erupted in steam. The workshop filled with billowing white clouds that hissed against hot metal. The Centurion's chest plate groaned as rapid cooling warped the brass. The amber glow dimmed — bright to pale to dark, the temperature dropping degree by degree.
The Matrix went inert. Cool. Dark.
Touchable.
The Run
Kyboh saw his chance and didn't hesitate.
He sprinted from cover — no enchantments, no tonal power, the Anchor of Stasis heavy on his neck, nothing but muscle and speed and the animal instinct to move when the opening appeared. The Centurion was blind but its hearing was perfect, and the sound of Kyboh's boots on stone drew it like a compass needle.
The hammer swung. Kyboh dropped to a slide, the massive brass head passing over him close enough to ruffle his fur. He came up running. The axe followed — a lateral sweep that would have cut him in half at the waist. He twisted, the blade passing so close it shaved a line of fur from his side.
Then the steam vent in the Centurion's chest fired.
The blast of superheated vapour caught Kyboh full in the face. The force hurled him backward — boots leaving the ground, body tumbling through the air, crashing into a workbench hard enough to crack the stone slab. He slid to the floor, gasping, skin red and raw where the steam had kissed him.
He didn't reach the Matrix. The Centurion stepped between him and the open chest, driven by sound, by the impacts Kyboh's body had made on every surface it hit. The blind guardian was learning the room through destruction — building a sonar map from the echoes of its own violence.
Orion raised his horn and played. The Movement of Entropy filled the workshop, the discordant frequencies weakening the Centurion's structure, making its movements fractionally slower, its joints fractionally stiffer. And every ally in range felt the surge — muscles recovering, focus sharpening, the fog of exhaustion lifting for one more push.
Then Varon moved.
The Shadowscale
He had been invisible for the entire fight. Not through magic — Varon had no magic to speak of. His invisibility was the product of a lifetime of training in the art of existing in spaces people forgot to look. While the party had scattered and hidden and fought, Varon had simply stood in a shadow and stopped being noticeable. The Centurion's life detection couldn't find him because he had no magical signature worth detecting. Its visual sensors were blinded. Its audio tracking was overwhelmed by louder targets.
Varon was the quietest thing in the room, and the room had forgotten he was there.
He unfolded from shadow the way water begins to move — no sudden transition, no explosive action, just a gradual shift from stillness to motion that accelerated with the fluid, inevitable certainty of a falling stone. He crossed the workshop floor in absolute silence, each step placed with the precision of a man who had been taught to walk on loose gravel without disturbing a single pebble.
The Centurion swung. Its hammer carved through the space where Varon had been a fraction of a second ago. Not because Varon had dodged — because Varon had never been there. He was already past the arc, inside the weapon's reach, his body flowing around the massive arm like a stream parting around a boulder.
The axe followed. Varon twisted sideways, the blade's edge passing close enough to scrape the surface of his armour without cutting through. He didn't flinch. He didn't slow. He was moving with the absolute commitment of someone who had calculated the odds, accepted the risk, and decided that the mathematics of dying were less important than the mathematics of success.
He reached into the Centurion's open chest and closed his fingers around the Aetherial Matrix.
It came free with a click — the sound of a locking mechanism disengaging, of a power source being removed from a system that had relied on it for forty centuries. The Centurion shuddered. The amber light in its eyes guttered. But the programming held. The last executed function — attack — locked into its mechanical brain, and the twelve-foot guardian continued to swing at anything that made sound, powered by residual charge and the stubborn momentum of four thousand years.
Varon turned from the Centurion, the Matrix in his hand, and looked across the workshop at Saijah.
He tried to smile.
It was the first genuinely human expression anyone had ever seen on his surgically modified face. The Breton-passing features — the rounded ears, the reshaped jaw, the carefully constructed mask of anonymity — shifted into something that looked almost natural. Almost warm. A crack in the professional armour, a single moment of unguarded pride offered to the woman he had been pursuing since the day he'd recognised her as clan and called her Vena.
He wanted her to see that he was more than cold efficiency. That the man inside the operative could be brave, and graceful, and worthy of the respect he was asking for.
Saijah saw it. She saw the smile and the vulnerability behind it and the calculation beneath the vulnerability, and she didn't know what to feel about any of it.
The distraction cost him.
The Centurion's foot came down in a massive stomp. The shockwave radiated outward through the workshop floor — cracking marble, splitting stone, throwing everything that wasn't bolted down into the air. Varon's legs went out from under him. He hit the ground hard, the Matrix clutched to his chest, the wind driven from his lungs. Across the room, Kyboh — still recovering from the steam blast — was knocked flat again by the same tremor.
But the Matrix was free. Varon had it. And the Centurion was running on fumes.
The Green Light
Ylva had been watching.
Through the entire infiltration — the planning, the approach, GEAR's catastrophic announcement, the blinding, the silent hunt, the key throw, the cooling, the extraction — she had stood at the back of the workshop with her axe in her hands and her jaw clenched and her blood simmering at a temperature that had nothing to do with the ambient heat.
She had joined the Wardens to fight. To hunt. To stand in front of something terrible and hit it until one of them stopped moving. Instead, she had watched Alfonso's tactics play out — the careful positioning, the coordinated magic, the letting-other-people-do-the-fighting that characterised every engagement since Korvanjund. She had braced at his side while thralls absorbed the punishment. She had stood guard while others got the glory. She had been leashed.
Alfonso caught her eye across the workshop. He saw the frustration boiling behind her grin. He saw the axe trembling in her grip.
He nodded.
Ylva's face split open in the widest smile of the entire campaign. She raised her axe — newly enchanted with Alfonso's lightning runes, the blade crackling with stored voltage that arced between the rune-lines like caged lightning — and charged.
"FINALLY!"
She hit the Centurion at a dead sprint. The enchanted blade bit into pristine Dwemer brass and discharged its lightning payload directly into the guardian's internal systems. Sparks erupted from the wound. Gears screamed. The sound of four thousand years of maintenance being violated in a single stroke rang through the workshop like a bell.
The Centurion staggered. Then it hit her back.
The backhand caught Ylva square in the chest — twelve feet of Dwemer engineering driving a brass fist into her ribcage with the force of a falling tree. She flew backward across the workshop, hit a pillar, bounced off it, and crashed to the floor in a heap of dented armour and red-gold braids.
She spat blood. Looked at the ceiling. Grinned.
"Finally a good fight!"
She rolled to her feet and charged again.
The Lightning
Everyone joined her.
Alfonso began charging — not the quick, efficient bolts of combat magic he'd used throughout the Midden, but a sustained channelling that turned his hands into conduits for raw electrical force. The power built slowly, crackling between his fingers, jumping to nearby metal surfaces, the air around him ionising until his hair stood on end and every brass fixture within ten feet sparked in sympathy.
Kyboh drew his lightning sword and fired a crackling bolt that arced across the workshop and struck the Centurion's shoulder joint. The brass fused. Gears welded themselves to gears. The arm locked in place, one weapon taken out of commission.
Davinia ran between the wounded, pouring healing magic and ice where it was needed — patching Varon's bruised ribs, stabilising Nora, clearing the steam burns from Kyboh's face with frost that numbed the pain before it could register.
Orion's horn sang without pause. The Movement of Entropy became a sustained composition, the discordant harmonics making every bolt land harder, every strike dig deeper, the Centurion's brass becoming brittle under the tonal assault.
Nora added her magic to the barrage. Tentative at first — thin lines of frost and sparks that she cast from behind cover, flinching with each release as if expecting her power to do something terrible. But the spells worked. They landed where she aimed them. They didn't summon anything from the void. And with each successful cast, her hands steadied, her aim sharpened, and the trembling girl from the storage closet became, for a few seconds at a time, the Master-level prodigy the College had always known was hiding behind the fear.
The Centurion fought with the mindless persistence of a machine running its last program. It swung. It stomped. It vented steam. But the lightning was inside it now — every enchanted arrow Saijah had planted between its plates, every bolt from Alfonso's sustained channel, every discharge from Ylva's axe — and the brass that had been its armour became a conductor for its own destruction. Sparks crawled across its frame. Gears ground against seized gears. The steam that vented from its joints carried the smell of burnt metal and ozone.
Ylva was in her element. She fought the way she'd always wanted to — not bracing, not guarding, not standing behind someone else's corpse army, but face to face with something that could kill her, trading blows with a grin that never wavered. Her axe rose and fell. The lightning discharged with each impact. The Centurion hit her again and she bounced back and hit it harder.
And through it all, moving through the chaos with the focused calm of someone who had already made her decision, Saijah was lining up her shot.
The Perfect Arrow
She wasn't looking at the chest — open, empty, the Matrix already removed. She wasn't looking at the limbs — damaged, sparking, but still functional. She was looking deeper. Past the brass. Past the gears. Past the engineering.
She was looking for the thing that made it run.
The central powerline. A single conduit through which every remaining charge flowed from the Centurion's soul gem housing in its head, through the spine of the machine, to the locomotion array in its legs. One line. Visible through the gaps in shattered brass plating as a thread of fading amber light, thin as a finger, carrying the last of the power that kept twelve feet of ancient engineering in motion.
She found it.
She drew her bow. One of Alfonso's lightning arrows — the rune-work still crackling, the charge still live. She calculated the angle. Through the gap in the chest where the Matrix had been. Through the internal mechanism — the interlocking gears, the spinning shafts, the reciprocating pistons. Through four thousand years of precision engineering that had never once anticipated an arrow threading through every component, every clearance, every tolerance, to reach the one wire that mattered.
The Centurion swung at Ylva. The timing was everything. The hammer-arm reached the end of its arc and the chest cavity opened to Saijah's angle for exactly one heartbeat.
She fired.
The arrow entered the Centurion's open chest and disappeared into its body. For a fraction of a second — a gap between heartbeats, a held breath across the workshop — nothing happened.
Then lightning crawled across the guardian's entire frame. Not from the outside in, but from the inside out. Every gear, every joint, every mechanism lit up with crackling discharge as the arrow's enchantment detonated along the central powerline. The electricity followed the conduit like fire follows a fuse, and everywhere it reached, systems died. Gears seized. Pistons locked. Joints fused solid.
The Centurion froze.
Not slowed. Frozen. Every system, every function, every last spark of residual charge extinguished in a single, cascading failure that propagated from core to extremity in less than a heartbeat.
It stood there for one eternal moment. Twelve feet of dead engineering, perfectly upright, wreathed in the fading glow of its own destruction.
Then the light went out of its eyes. And it was still.
The workshop fell silent. The party stood among the wreckage — shattered workbenches, scorched stone, the smell of ozone and hot brass hanging in the air like incense — and stared at the machine that Saijah had killed with a single arrow through its heart.
"Saijah," Kyboh said.
She lowered her bow.
"Yeah?"
"That was the best shot I've ever seen."
She allowed herself a small smile. Her hands were perfectly steady. Her migraine had gone quiet. For one moment, standing in the ruins of a Dwemer workshop four hundred feet underground, surrounded by the wreckage of a fight that should have killed them all, Saijah felt exactly like what she was.
The best archer in Skyrim.

PART IV: THE SMALL FILE
The Maintenance Request
GEAR rolled forward from wherever he'd been hiding during the fight. His amber lens clicked on the empty chest cavity, on the dark eyes, on the motionless limbs. The Centurion stood above him like a brass colossus, and GEAR studied it with the specific attention of someone cataloguing a change in inventory.
"What fun!" he announced, his voice carrying the bright tone of a researcher who had just collected excellent data. "The combat data was most informative. I have updated my files on organic tactical decision-making. Your approach to the kinetic targeting problem was highly creative, if structurally inelegant."
Then his eye moved to the Centurion's face. The dark gems. The empty chest.
"Oh dear."
His voice shifted. Not dramatically — GEAR didn't have the vocal range for drama. But something in the modulation changed. Something that sounded less like reporting and more like understanding.
"That is suboptimal. The Primary Unit has ceased function."
He was quiet for a moment. His lens dimmed.
"I will log a maintenance request."
Another pause. Longer this time. The amber barely glowing.
"Though I suppose no one is coming to fulfil it. Are they."
From a crevice in the wall, a single Spider Worker scuttled out. It was small — smaller than the sentinels they'd fought on the surface, smaller than the janitors that maintained the corridors above. A maintenance unit. The lowest tier of Dwemer automation, designed for one purpose.
It ignored the party entirely. It climbed the motionless Centurion's leg with careful, deliberate steps, each of its eight brass legs finding purchase on the pristine surface it had probably cleaned a thousand times before. It reached the shattered chest plate and began to work.
It tightened a broken gear that would never turn again. It tried to seal a steam pipe that had stopped carrying pressure hours ago. Its manipulator arms probed the ruined hardware with the methodical patience of a creature that had been doing this exact job since before the First Era, following protocols that had never included a subroutine for "give up."
Thirty seconds.
Then it stopped. Its legs retracted slightly. It sat on the Centurion's shoulder for a moment — still, quiet, its tiny sensor-eye clicking once on the empty chest where the Matrix had been.
It climbed back down. Retreated to its crevice. Disappeared into the wall.
Nobody spoke.
The workshop was very quiet. The amber lamps still burned. The ventilation still hummed. The sterile air still circulated through corridors where nobody breathed. And in the morning — or whatever passed for morning in a place that had never seen the sun — the spider would come back. It would climb the Centurion's leg again. It would try to fix the broken gear. It would fail. It would leave. And it would come back again the next day, and the next, and the next, following a maintenance schedule that stretched forward into a future where nobody would ever check its work.
GEAR watched the crevice where the spider had disappeared. His lens was still dim. His legs were still.
Then he turned back to the party, eye brightening with what might have been determination, or might have been the closest a four-thousand-year-old brass sphere could come to deciding that the past was past and the present was standing in front of him wearing exhaustion and blood and the specific look of people who needed someone to tell them what to do next.
"Shall we proceed?" he asked.
They collected what they could from the wreckage. Davinia took the Centurion's axe-hand — a weapon designed for a twelve-foot frame, Dwemer engineering at its most brutal, the blade still sharp after millennia. Saijah claimed the spears from the weapon rack. Alfonso took the hammer-hand, turning it over in his grip, studying the tonal mechanisms with the focused interest of someone who heard music in everything.
Varon held the Aetherial Matrix. He sat against the far wall, the crystal cradled in both hands, watching it pulse. It was cool now — body temperature, steady, the amber light throbbing with a rhythm like a sleeping heartbeat. He hadn't offered it to anyone. Nobody had asked for it yet.
Kyboh was across the room, flexing his bare hands. He'd taken the Anchor of Stasis off before the fight — shoved it into his pack so he could use his enchanted sword, his enchanted boots, the gear that made him dangerous. Hjolmar had told him not to. Hjolmar had been very clear: the Anchor stays on until the gauntlet is finished, no enchantments, no exceptions, or the bone enchantment will activate without a regulator and every use will cost him. Kyboh had nodded at the time. He'd understood, in the way he always understood things — long enough to agree, not long enough to remember when it mattered.
He wasn't thinking about the Matrix in Varon's hands. He wasn't thinking about what would happen when enchanted bones met an unshielded tonal stabiliser. He was thinking about how good it felt to have his sword back, how fast the boots made him, how the fight had been close and loud and real in a way that made the silence afterward feel earned.
The psychic static was back. He barely noticed.
They stood in the workshop of the dead, holding pieces of a machine that had outlived its makers by millennia, and breathed.

— End of The Heart of Brass —

